<TEXT>
a world war ii veteran paralyzed from the chest 
down left friday on a solo 4669mile transatlantic flight to the 
german battlefield where he was wounded in world war ii 
clark harrison a 63yearold real estate company owner and bank 
chairman in suburban decatur took off from dekalbpeachtree 
airport about 930 am friday in a singleengine cherokee piper 
equipped with hand controls 
he is scheduled to arrive at aachen west germany on july 11 
and attend a reception in nearby stolberg where he was wounded by 
a sniper during a battle four days after he landed following the 
normandy invasion 
what scares me the most is rolling around in this wheelchair 
and getting in and out of it he said the easy part is the 
flying once i get on the ground thats the hard part 
harrison plans to fly his spirit of shepherd airplane up the 
eastern seaboard and across canada to the us air force base at 
sondrestrom greenland where he plans to spend the fourth of july 
flying by visual flight rules about 2000 feet above the ground 
harrison then will cross the greenland ice cap and go on to 
reykjavik iceland bagar island in the faeroe islands stornoway 
scotland biggin hill england and aachen 
harrison flies in a cramped twoseat cockpit filled with his 
wheelchair his luggage a life raft survival kit and an auxiliary 
fuel tank he gets in and out of the plane by crawling onto the 
wing which sits about three feet off the ground and then pulling 
the wheelchair up or letting it down with a strap 
he hopes the trip will raise money for a center for independent 
living at the shepherd spinal center in atlanta he is a founding 
director of the 13yearold shepherd spinal center in atlanta 
supporters are pledging to donate to the hospital up to 1 for each 
mile harrison plans to travel 
