a presidential panel trying to resolve a 
dispute between the chicago amp northwestern transportation co and 
one of its unions is offering a compromise that would preserve some 
jobs and prevent a threatened strike 
the white house released a 29page report late friday in which 
an emergency board said both sides should make sacrifices 
the report also recommended arbitration if the nations 
eighthlargest railroad and the united transportation union cannot 
agree on specific personnel cuts 
at issue is a cnw proposal to eliminate the jobs of 1050 utu 
brakemen by cutting the size of its train crews from four to two 
workers an engineer and conductor in most cases 
spokeswoman leslie cleveland said chicago amp northwestern could 
save about 51 million a year by reducing manpower calling it a 
necessary step to remain competitive 
however the union characterized the cuts affecting half its cnw 
members as a contract violation and demanded no change from the 
status quo 
it threatened to strike on april 22 prompting president reagan 
to appoint the emergency board under the railway labor act 
the carrier unlike many of the other railroads in the 
industry has an economic need for relief from its present 
crewconsist rules the board said this is not to say 
that the employees alone should be expected to bear the burden 
although the board said cnw should be allowed to eliminate one 
brakemen per train it recommended that further reductions be 
decided by an arbitration board casebycase 
the panel also said cnw should be able to terminate some workers 
if not enough accept voluntary separation allowances but it also 
recommended raising the railroads proposed 25000 allowance to 
50000 for employees leaving voluntarily and 45000 for those 
forced into separation 
company officials said they had not seen the report and had no 
immediate comment friday 
donald f markgraf the unions general chairman said these 
things work out in strange ways sometimes were still hoping for a 
settlement 
a strike cannot begin before 1201 am aug 4 said roland 
watkins an administrative assistant to the emergency board 
chicago amp northwestern ranks eighth among us railroads in 
revenue and handled nearly 15 million carloads of traffic in 1986 
it also provides the principal daily rail service for about 40000 
commuters in the chicago area 
