tamil militants in sri lanka are ready 
to surrender but negotiations have stalled because the rebels are 
demanding 384 million from the indian government tamil sources 
said 
sources close to the rebels in colombo speaking on condition of 
anonymity said friday the militants were not willing to allow 
monitoring of how the money was spent 
in the southern indian city of madras sadasivam krishnakumar a 
senior member of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam was quoted 
as saying the group was willing to surrender but awaited final 
orders from its commander 
the tigers the largest rebel group in sri lanka have been at 
the forefront of the fiveyear guerrilla war with the ethnic 
sinhalesedominated government for an independent tamil homeland 
india which has 50000 peacekeeping troops in sri lanka has 
been trying to negotiate an end to the separatist war in the 
neighboring island nation 
the sri lankan government on thursday offered amnesty to the 
rebels and promised to conduct provincial elections by the end of 
july in northern and eastern sri lanka where the rebels want a 
separate homeland 
the united news of india quoted krishnakumar as telling 
reporters in madras that the tigers would participate in the 
provincial electionsbut he said no decision had been made on 
whether the tigers organization would participate in the elections 
itself or would form a new political party the news agency said 
