<TEXT>
national lawmakers are preparing 
for final voting on the draft of a new constitution that would 
reject sweeping land reform but liberalize work rules and end 
foreign control of mining 
the new charter for south americas largest country would also 
give president jose sarney and his successors a fiveyear term a 
victory for the national leader 
the proposed document was born in five months of heated debate 
in the congress doubling as a constitutional convention it has 
come up 235 articles that will be the basis for the eighth 
constitution in the 166 years of brazils independence from 
portugal 
the final round of voting is expected to start near the end of 
july but the document appears largely to have assumed its final 
form because a hefty 280 votes in the 559member convention would 
be needed to change it 
the convention made up of representatives and senators picked 
in free elections in 1986 began rewriting the current 
constitution dictated during a 19641985 military regime in 
february 1987 
the project started with a computergenerated document touching 
nearly every aspect of life imaginable in this country of about 140 
million people it then progressed to a first draft of more than 
3000 articles which critics derided as an encyclopedia 
the real paring began last february with articlebyarticle 
voting in which a majority of 280 was needed for approval 
lawmakers debated vociferously sometimes violently especially 
about issues like land reform workers rights and the role of 
foreign capital 
other hotly contested matters involved how long sarney the 
civilian who assumed office in 1985 should stay there and whether 
brazil should have a ustype presidential form of government or a 
europeanstyle prime minister system 
as it stands the proposed constitution contains these 
provisions 
sarney and future presidents will serve for five years 
compared to the six years of former military presidents the 
presidential system remains in place 
wideranging land reform in a country where 4 percent of the 
people own 50 percent of the farmable land was rejected 
workers appear headed for a shorter work week and more liberal 
vacation benefits but a liberal maternity leave program might not 
survive the final vote because businesses view it as too expensive 
foreign companies involved in mining will have to leave brazil 
in four years or transfer financial control to residents of the 
country 
risk contracts allowing foreign companies to drill for oil 
probably wont be continued 
the return of legalized casino gambling was rejected 
the biggest fight broke out between sarney and convention 
members over the length of the presidential term 
tancredo neves a moderate who said he wanted only four years as 
president before holding elections died before taking office in 
1985 brazils last presidential election was in 1960 sarney vice 
presidentelect and former chief of the military regimes official 
party moved into the presidency 
he made it clear he believed he had inherited the sixyear term 
of his military predecessor gen joao figueiredo but said he 
would consider stepping down after five years 
however many congressmen wanted sarney out after four years 
with presidential elections in november 1988 
sarney won his five years in the constitutional debating but at 
the cost of splitting his brazilian democratic movement party 
various groups are still seeking changes in the final form of 
the document 
a conservative block known as the big center is trying to 
gain support to strike the antiforeign articles involving mining 
and oil prospecting and a proposition allowing civil servants 
strike under certain circumstances 
leftists including members of brazils two small communist 
parties want to try to knock out conservative provisions on land 
reform and one that lets civilian powers call in the armed forces 
to deal with internal problems 
there is no time limit for the last round of debate 
but rep ulysses guimaraes speaker of brazils house and 
president of the constitutional convention says he would like 
officially to proclaim the new constitution on sept 7 the 
national holiday that commemmorates independence 
