<TEXT>
in recent days michael dukakis campaigned in 
mississipi and indiana states that have backed a democratic 
presidential hopeful only once in 28 years this week republican 
george bush is going to dukakis hometown for a greek orthodox 
church dinner 
no these presidential candidates arent just wasting their 
time looking for votes in all the wrong places 
these events are early feints in the general election campaign 
a strategy called attacking your opponents base it is one piece 
of putting together the electoral college puzzle to win 270 
electoral votes and the white house on nov 8 
if bush is tied down in places like indiana and the south 
hes going to have a hard time doing what he needs to win the 
election said democratic pollster mark mellman 
its a smart strategy for both sides said vince breglio a 
republican campaign tactician its not defending your solid core 
vote its the marginal voters who are part of your base they are 
part of the core but not a dependable part 
of course bush and dukakis are looking for every possible vote 
in the fall 
the theory behind the attacking the base strategy is 
straightforward if a candidate must spend his time making certain 
the people who usually vote for his party will back him he wont 
have time to win the swing voters who have been increasingly 
crucial to victory in this country 
for example dukakis has campaigned across the south and the 
farm belt in the midwest regions that have been very strong for 
the republicans thus if bush must defend his base of support in 
those areas he will have less time to campaign in california new 
york pennsylvania and ohio where the gop needs to do well 
while such a strategy is used in all kinds of races it is 
particularly important in a presidential campaign because of the 
electoral college system 
winning the most votes doesnt mean winning the white house a 
candidate must win enough states to gain a majority of the 538 
electoral votes at stake to succeed ronald reagan in 1989 
of course bush dukakis and their aides proclaim that they will 
battle for every state in the fall taking nothing for granted and 
conceding nothing 
its not designed to make dukakis pay attention to his base 
said bush spokesman mark goodin of the thursday trip to boston 
its an indication that we are not going to take anything for 
granted 
dukakis spokesman leslie dach said the massachusetts governors 
strength and campaigning all across the country makes it tough for 
bush and the gop 
in their grand plan they thought they didnt have to secure 
landing rights in big regions of the country dach said now 
theyre finding they have to lease apartments everywhere 
the reality is that there are limited resources for a 
presidential campaign and limited time for a candidates 
campaigning 
once things have started to solidify im sure the dukakis 
campaign will sit down and make a careful assessment of where to 
concentrate the resources mellman said 
the starting point of any electoral college strategy and the 
attacking the base tactic is history and history is on the 
side of bush and the republicans 
one way to look at electoral history is the percentage of the 
twoparty vote for each candidate from 1952 through 1984 mellman 
points out that democrats have averaged a majority of the vote in 
only six states and the district of columbia over that period 
thats a total of 52 electoral votes from georgia hawaii 
massachusetts minnesota rhode island west virginia and the 
district of columbia 
the republicans have averaged at least 55 percent of the vote in 
27 states through the same elections for 208 electoral votes 
thus democrats would have to win 218 electoral votes among the 
17 remaining states to add to their base to return to power in the 
white house the gop could hold onto its historic base and win the 
white house with only 62 electoral votes from the 278 available in 
those swing states 
but dukakis aides say the appeal to history is a misleading one 
saying the republican spokesmen are trying to erect a historical 
barrier between michael dukakis and the voters 
democrats point to such states as iowa a traditionally 
republican state where dukakis has a substantial lead in the 
polls 
in addition a purely regional strategy is tough to pull off as 
differences between the regions shrink and the influence of 
national television coverage grows 
the best thing to do is cherrypick mellman says taking 
a state here in the south and one there 
with the national polls moving dramatically in recent weeks 
breglio agrees that the fall campaign is going to be 
handtohand statebystate combat as bush and dukakis try for 
the magic majority of 270 electoral votes 
