<TEXT>
us officials say new zealand may be able to 
restore military cooperation with the united states with a formula 
similar to that which keeps antinuclear denmark in the north 
atlantic treaty organization 
the subject came up after both us and australian leaders 
voiced regret here the past week at the absence of new zealand from 
the third straight annual ministerial meeting of anzus the 
military alliance formed by the three pacific countries after world 
war ii 
usnew zealand military ties deteriorated after prime minister 
david lange in 1985 barred a visiting us warship under his new 
labor party governments decision to close new zealand territory to 
nucleararmed ships the united states later read new zealand out 
of anzus in order to protect its policy of refusing to confirm or 
deny whether any ship carries nuclear weapons 
there must be a formula if new zealand would only look for 
it that would make it possible for them to come back into the 
fold us secretary of state george shultz told reporters last 
wednesday after a twoday meeting with australian leaders 
asked to elaborate on shultzs remark another high us 
official told reporters friday one formula they might look at i 
suppose is the danish formula 
another state department official described the danish formula 
as informing their allies by letter that denmark does not permit 
calls at their ports by ships armed with nuclear weapons and leave 
it at that 
the us officials spoke on condition they not be identified 
denmark and the united states have announced settlement of a 
dispute similar to the usnew zealand controversy that erupted 
when the danish parliament in april adopted a resolution requiring 
the government to notify visiting warships of denmarks 31yearold 
ban on nuclear weapons 
after new but inconclusive elections waged partly on the 
issue denmarks coalition prime minister poul schlueter told the 
parliament on june 7 that allied governments had been informed of 
denmarks general policy banning atomic weapons during peacetime 
and that in cases of specific ship visits foreign governments would 
be told that denmark assumes the visit is in compliance with danish 
rules 
the government considers that this procedure respects both the 
danish nonnuclear policy and the views of our allies schlueter 
said 
state department spokesman charles redman said june 7 the united 
states had noted the prime ministers statement and one by danish 
foreign minister uffe ellemannjensen that the formula respects 
the policy of our allies neither to confirm nor to deny the 
presence of nuclear weapons on their naval vessels 
us officials have said a similar arrangement is used on us 
port visits to norway 
new zealand has not recently suggested using the danish formula 
and it would be up to it to take the initiative on the matter said 
one of the state department officials prime minister lange in the 
past has likened new zealands nuclear ban to those of the 
scandinavian nato allies 
</TEXT>
